english:
  title: Memorial of Gratitude for an Imperial Edict Granting a Banquet at the Longevity Hall
  author: Byeon Gye-ryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your Majesty's wisdom runs deep and true,
    Your praise shines forth with clarity.
    Such generous grace overwhelms my heart—
    I stand trembling, lost for words.

    Yet I reflect: my nature is dull and slow,
    My talents crude and rough as stone.
    By fortune's hand, I met the Sacred Reign,
    And received a fief, unworthy though I am.
    Sixteen years have passed without a thread of service,
    Three thousand leagues away, yet bathed in royal favor.
    Measuring my worth against such kindness,
    Even dust ground to powder cannot repay.

    Of late, old ailments plague me oft,
    And I lack strength for governing affairs.
    I humbly laid my case before the throne,
    And graciously, you eased my heavy burden.
    My ailing frame found rest at last,
    My foolish son beholds advancement's light.

    Unexpected came the imperial messenger,
    Bearing tokens of your boundless love.
    Your words, so tender and sincere,
    As if I stood before your very face.
    At the splendid feast I drank my fill,
    And felt your grace seep through my very bones.

    You spoke of one who serves the court with reverence,
    Who guards his realm with steadfast care—
    Clear-sighted, deep of heart, seasoned with age.
    I ask myself: what man am I
    To merit such words of praise?
    Reading them, my tears flow without end.

    This great benevolence extends even to my children,
    As heaven and earth rejoice together.
    Joyful songs fill the eastern sky,
    And histories will record this favor for ages to come.
    Such gentle kindness is rare in all antiquity.

    This springs from Your Majesty's boundless heart,
    Your nourishing grace that cherishes all things,
    Unwilling to cast aside what time has worn,
    Bending deep with love toward humble servants.
    Thus, even one as lowly as I,
    Can look up and receive heaven's gift of life.

    I vow, from dawn to dusk,
    To pray that your years equal the heavens,
    And that my children's children,
    May ever guard with reverence the land you have bestowed.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Byeon Gye-ryang (1369-1430) was a Korean official of the early Joseon dynasty who served as governor of a provincial domain. This memorial was written upon receiving imperial recognition and a banquet invitation.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Longevity Hall' (Sugang-jeon) refers to a hall where celebrations of longevity and auspicious occasions were held.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Sixteen years'' refers to the duration of Byeon''s tenure in his post.'
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase 'heaven and earth rejoice together' reflects the Korean Confucian belief that imperial virtue harmonizes the cosmic order.
